      Not everything is securities fraud
   =20
 =20

=E2=80=9CEverything is securities fraud,=E2=80=9D I like to say around here=
, meaning:
=09Sometimes a public company does a bad thing, or has a bad thing happen t=
o it.=09News of the bad thing comes out and the stock drops.=09Shareholders=
 sue, saying =E2=80=9Cyou didn=E2=80=99t tell us about the bad thing in adv=
ance, so we bought the stock thinking there was no bad thing, but then we f=
ound out that there was a bad thing. We were defrauded; we overpaid for the=
 stock because of your lies.=E2=80=9D

Occasionally I add a technical clarification: Simply=C2=A0not mentioning=C2=
=A0a bad thing is not fraud=C2=A0under US securities law. The law (Rule 10b=
-5) says that it=E2=80=99s fraud =E2=80=9Cto make any untrue statement of a=
 material fact or to omit to state a material fact necessary in order to ma=
ke the statements made, in the light of the circumstances under which they =
were made, not misleading.=E2=80=9D So=C2=A0lying=C2=A0=E2=80=94=C2=A0sayin=
g something that isn=E2=80=99t true =E2=80=94=C2=A0is securities fraud. And=
 many=C2=A0omissions=C2=A0are securities fraud, if the company omits inform=
ation that is =E2=80=9Cnecessary in order to make the statements made =E2=
=80=A6=C2=A0not misleading.=E2=80=9D (So for instance if a company=E2=80=99=
s public statements say =E2=80=9Cwe have an ethics policy and try to be eth=
ical,=E2=80=9D and omit to mention =E2=80=9Cour executives did an unethical=
 thing,=E2=80=9D somebody will sue over that, claiming that the description=
 of the ethics policy was misleadingly positive.)
But it is not securities fraud=C2=A0simply not to mention a bad thing. If a=
 bad thing happens, and the company doesn=E2=80=99t say anything about it, =
and it doesn=E2=80=99t say anything that might be misleading, that=E2=80=99=
s not securities fraud. This does not come up that often, because companies=
 are always going around saying generic things that might be contradicted b=
y their bad news. If a company has a sexual harassment scandal, its stateme=
nts about its ethics policy might be misleading; if it has a computer hack,=
 its statements about its information security policy might be misleading; =
etc. But in theory pure silence is not securities fraud.
Still, you could imagine pure silence being misleading. For instance, you c=
ould imagine things that the market would=C2=A0expect to be disclosed=C2=A0=
if they happened, so that=C2=A0not=C2=A0disclosing them sort of implies tha=
t they didn=E2=80=99t happen. If a company=E2=80=99s chief executive office=
r died suddenly, and the company=C2=A0didn=E2=80=99t tell anyone=C2=A0for a=
 few weeks, that would be weird! The company hasn=E2=80=99t lied, but every=
one kind of went around assuming that the CEO was alive, and the company di=
dn=E2=80=99t bother to correct their mistaken impression.
Or: There are a lot of US Securities and Exchange Commission rules requirin=
g companies to disclose certain things. Regulation S-K, for instance, requi=
res companies to disclose certain specific=C2=A0types of information about =
their business in their quarterly filings: Companies are supposed to=C2=A0=
=E2=80=9Cdescribe any known trends or uncertainties that have had or that a=
re reasonably likely to have a material favorable or unfavorable impact on =
net sales or revenues or income from continuing operations,=E2=80=9D =E2=80=
=9Cdescribe briefly any material pending legal proceedings,=E2=80=9D discus=
s =E2=80=9Cmaterial factors that make an investment in the registrant or of=
fering speculative or risky,=E2=80=9D etc.=C2=A0
If the law says that you have to disclose any material lawsuits in your qua=
rterly report on Form 10-Q, and there is some material lawsuit against you,=
 and you file a 10-Q and don=E2=80=99t mention the lawsuit, then that is ar=
guably misleading. =E2=80=9CIf there was a lawsuit, they would be required =
to mention it, and they didn=E2=80=99t mention a lawsuit, so there must not=
 be one,=E2=80=9D investors could reasonably conclude. The omission,=C2=A0c=
ombined with the reporting requirement, is misleading. If Form 10-Q consist=
ed of a literal form with a box saying =E2=80=9CAre there any material laws=
uits against you,=E2=80=9D and you wrote =E2=80=9Cno,=E2=80=9D the =E2=80=
=9Cno=E2=80=9D would be a false statement. Arguably just leaving out the re=
quired disclosure has the same effect.
Anyway that is the view of the US Securities and Exchange Commission:

An MD&A [management=E2=80=99s discussion and analysis] that makes certain s=
tatements but omits information that [Regulation S-K] Item 303 requires to =
be included is a misleading half-truth.=C2=A0... By filing an MD&A describi=
ng certain known trends and uncertainties, an issuer makes statements. If t=
he issuer omits other known trends or uncertainties that meet Item 303=E2=
=80=99s threshold, the MD&A=E2=80=99s statements will be misleading to a re=
asonable investor, who will be aware of Item 303=E2=80=99s requirement to l=
ist all material known trends or uncertainties, and therefore will assume t=
hat the MD&A provides a complete list. =E2=80=A6
Where regulatory disclosure requirements apply, reasonable investors will i=
nfer from an issuer=E2=80=99s silence that the types of events for which di=
sclosure is required have not occurred.

Macquarie Infrastructure Corp. operated terminals for=C2=A0No. 6 fuel oil. =
In 2016, the United Nations essentially banned No. 6 fuel oil by 2020. But:
In the ensuing years, Macquarie did not discuss IMO 2020 [the UN ban] in it=
s public offering documents. In February 2018, however, Macquarie announced=
 a drop in the amount of storage contracted for use by its subsidiary due i=
n part to the decline in the No. 6 fuel oil market. Macquarie=E2=80=99s sto=
ck price fell 41%.
Shareholders naturally sued, arguing that (1) Regulation S-K=C2=A0required =
Macquarie to =E2=80=9Cdescribe any known trends or uncertainties that have =
had or that are reasonably likely to have a material favorable or unfavorab=
le impact on net sales or revenues or income from continuing operations,=E2=
=80=9D (2) this was a known trend or uncertainty that was likely to be bad =
for sales, (3) Macquarie did not disclose it and (4) that was misleading. M=
acquarie argued that it couldn=E2=80=99t be securities fraud just to=C2=A0n=
ot mention=C2=A0the new UN rule. The district court agreed and dismissed th=
e lawsuit, but an appeals court disagreed, finding that, when there=E2=80=
=99s a rule requiring disclosure of something, it can be fraud not to discl=
ose the thing.
Macquarie appealed to the Supreme Court, and last Friday it won. The unanim=
ous Supreme Court said:
The question in this case is whether the failure to disclose information re=
quired by Item 303 can support a private action under Rule 10b=E2=80=935(b)=
, even if the failure does not render any =E2=80=9Cstatements made=E2=80=9D=
 misleading. The Court holds that it cannot. Pure omissions are not actiona=
ble under Rule 10b=E2=80=935(b).
I guess that is the better reading of the actual words of the rule, though =
it is a weird reading of its intent. Omitting things that you=E2=80=99re re=
quired to disclose really does seem misleading.=C2=A0In any case, there you=
 go, some things are not securities fraud.


