Merger agreements are long and boring and most people don=E2=80=99t read th=
em all the way through. In theory, this might make them a good place for tr=
icks. If you are selling your company, maybe you could try putting on page =
47: =E2=80=9CNotwithstanding anything else in this agreement,=C2=A0Buyer sh=
all pay Seller an amount in cash equal to the product of (1) the Purchase P=
rice and (2) two (2).=E2=80=9D Maybe no one will notice, everyone will sign=
 the contract, you=E2=80=99ll get to closing, the buyer will hand you a che=
ck for the agreed purchase price, and you=E2=80=99ll say =E2=80=9Cno actual=
ly on page 47 it says you have to give me twice this amount.=E2=80=9D The b=
uyer will flip to page 47 and say =E2=80=9Chuh I missed that but come on, t=
hat was not the deal,=E2=80=9D you will say =E2=80=9Cno, it was the deal, i=
t=E2=80=99s right there in the contract,=E2=80=9D you=E2=80=99ll go to cour=
t, and the judge will say =E2=80=9Cwell this is mighty weird but a contract=
 is a contract so here=E2=80=99s your money.=E2=80=9D
In practice, you do not hear much about this sort of thing in big mergers a=
nd acquisitions, for several reasons:
=09Many mergers are fairly collaborative, friendly endeavors. The buyer is =
buying a business that it likes, it is working with the seller to make sure=
 the business is as good as possible, everyone is trying to win each other=
=E2=80=99s trust, and often it is better to win points by saying =E2=80=9Ch=
ey we noticed that this formula would underpay you, let=E2=80=99s fix it=E2=
=80=9D than it is to try to sneak a tricky formula into the contract.=09Par=
ties to merger agreements have=C2=A0huge=C2=A0incentives to catch tricks, a=
nd they pay lawyers to read the contracts and look out for tricks.
  [1]

=09Mergers are often one-shot deals for the seller =E2=80=94=C2=A0after the=
 merger, the target company vanishes =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there are a lot of =
repeat players around. Private equity firms and big companies do a lot of a=
cquisitions, and developing a reputation for trickiness might make that har=
der. Their professionals =E2=80=94=C2=A0bankers and lawyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0=
also do lots of deals, for buyers and sellers, and also care about their re=
putation.
  [2]

=09This is not legal advice, but as a broad generalization,=C2=A0if there i=
s something in a merger agreement that is=C2=A0manifestly a trick, and you =
go to court to enforce it, there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that a judge wil=
l say =E2=80=9Coh come on that=E2=80=99s a trick, you can=E2=80=99t enforce=
 that,=E2=80=9D and your trick won=E2=80=99t work. It=E2=80=99s possible th=
at a judge will say =E2=80=9Ca contract is a contract and congratulations o=
n your trick,=E2=80=9D but it=E2=80=99s also quite possible that she won=E2=
=80=99t, and will be annoyed, and you=E2=80=99ll be in a worse place than i=
f you hadn=E2=80=99t done the trick at all.

I have become a bit of a connoisseur of contractual trickiness around here,=
 and also in my previous careers.
  [3]
=C2=A0But mostly I am sort of an efficient-markets guy, in many areas of li=
fe, and I tend to assume that most big-dollar high-finance contracts probab=
ly say what people expect them to say.
But last week at FT Alphaville, Sujeet Indap had a wild story about Save Ma=
rt, a closely held supermarket whose family owners sold it in 2022 to Kings=
wood Capital Management. Kingswood agreed to pay the sellers $245 million, =
net of cash and debt; at closing, the sellers swept about $200 million of c=
ash from the company, and Kingswood wrote them a check for about $40 millio=
n.
  [4]
 And then a few months later, Kingswood sent the sellers a bill for $87 mil=
lion, effectively asking them to pay Kingswood=C2=A0for taking over the com=
pany. =E2=80=9CThe saga is a window into the vagaries of private-company de=
almaking,=E2=80=9D writes Indap,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand how esoteric financial a=
ccounting can be weaponised by a canny counterparty.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s =
the rare trick M&A!
Here is the trick. Save Mart owned a one-third interest in a joint venture =
called Superstore Industries. It carried this interest on its books as an e=
quity investment. Superstore, meanwhile, had $109 million of its own debt, =
which Save Mart apparently guaranteed, but which was not reflected on Save =
Mart=E2=80=99s balance sheet: Save Mart=E2=80=99s balance sheet showed only=
 the $22.5 million value of its equity investment in Superstore (net of tha=
t debt and its partners=E2=80=99 equity interests). And part of what Kingsw=
ood was buying from Save Mart was that equity interest.
The way the purchase agreement worked was that, after closing, there was a =
true-up based on the final balance sheet of Save Mart at closing. Basically=
 if Save Mart had more debt than expected, the sellers would have to pay Ki=
ngswood for the extra debt: You take the company=E2=80=99s actual debt at c=
losing, subtract the debt reflected on the pre-closing balance sheet, and t=
he sellers pay Kingswood back an adjustment for any excess. If the sellers =
went on a borrowing spree just before closing, and then paid the cash out t=
o themselves, they=E2=80=99d have to pay it back to Kingswood in the true-u=
p.
But the purchase agreement=E2=80=99s definition of =E2=80=9CClosing Date In=
debtedness=E2=80=9D included Save Mart=E2=80=99s own debt and also debt tha=
t it guaranteed. This means that:
=09The $109 million Superstore debt counts, under the terms of the purchase=
 agreement, as Save Mart=C2=A0debt at closing.=09It was=C2=A0not=C2=A0refle=
cted on the pre-closing balance sheet, because it is not Save Mart debt und=
er accounting rules.=09Therefore, you take the $109 million debt, you subtr=
act the=C2=A0zero=C2=A0dollars of that debt reflected on the balance sheet,=
 and that=E2=80=99s the true-up that the sellers owe to Kingswood.

Kingswood paid the sellers about $40 million for the company at the closing=
 on March 28, 2022. And then in July, it sent them a post-closing statement=
, asking them to=C2=A0pay it back $87 million. (The $87 million apparently=
=C2=A0reflected the $109 million debt, minus other post-closing adjustments=
 in the sellers=E2=80=99 favor.) So the total purchase price of the company=
 would be negative.
The sellers replied to the effect =E2=80=9Cno obviously that debt doesn=E2=
=80=99t count, that=E2=80=99s not the deal, we=E2=80=99re not paying.=E2=80=
=9D Kingswood replied =E2=80=9Cwell the purchase agreement says it counts, =
so pay up.=E2=80=9D They went to arbitration, and the arbitrator =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0a former Delaware Chancery Court=C2=A0judge =E2=80=94=C2=A0ruled in f=
avor of Kingswood, finding that=C2=A0obviously they didn=E2=80=99t mean=C2=
=A0for the sellers to have to pay for all that debt, but that=E2=80=99s wha=
t the contract says, and a contract is a contract:=C2=A0

The buyer relies heavily on the definitions in the purchase agreement to ar=
gue that the parties contemplated potential downward adjustments to the pur=
chase price to account for debt that resided within the target=E2=80=99s su=
bsidiaries.=C2=A0The seller acknowledges the buyer has not misread the appl=
icable definitions, but argues the proper construction of those definitions=
 must account for other provisions in the contract that reflect the parties=
=E2=80=99 intent that the sizable debt at issue would not be counted in the=
 purchase price adjustment. ...
Extrinsic evidence, says the seller, reveals that the parties never intende=
d for the debt at issue=C2=A0to be part of the purchase price adjustment. F=
or its part, the buyer struggles to explain much of this extrinsic evidence=
, but maintains the adjustment is entirely consistent with the parties=E2=
=80=99 overarching understanding that the sale would be a cash free, debt f=
ree transaction. =E2=80=A6
Delaware law is more contractarian than most, and Delaware courts will enfo=
rce the letter of the parties=E2=80=99 contract without regard for whether =
they have struck a good deal or bad deal.=C2=A0

Kingswood and the sellers then went to the actual Delaware Chancery Court, =
which disagreed with the arbitrator but had to defer to his decision. So Ki=
ngswood gets its money. The sellers are appealing to the Delaware Supreme C=
ourt.
To be fair, this is not exactly a trick in the contract; it=E2=80=99s a tri=
ck in the balance sheet, or perhaps a tricky interaction between the two. I=
ndap quotes the Kingswood deal guy:

We were surprised that the seller didn=E2=80=99t put any SSI debt in their =
definition of indebtedness as of the closing, and our view was, if=C2=A0tha=
t=E2=80=99s what they believed and we raised it, we thought=C2=A0it would b=
e a contentious topic=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.
Again, we had had a draft purchase agreement from them dating back to, you =
know, December that clearly laid out the debt of operating=C2=A0subsidiarie=
s, as well as debt guaranteed by Save Mart=C2=A0was, in fact, indebtedness =
for purposes of the transaction. Again, it=E2=80=99s a very standard defini=
tion.=C2=A0So no, we assumed that they had read their own document that the=
y drafted=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89
Because our perspective was, per the purchase agreement, SSI debt was to be=
 included in indebtedness. For some reason, which we don=E2=80=99t know why=
, that appeared not to be the perspective of the seller at the=C2=A0time th=
at they delivered the preclosing statement.

Indap writes: =E2=80=9CIn other words, Kingswood had believed, all along pr=
ior to signing and closing, that the gross SSI debt belonged on Save Mart=
=E2=80=99s main balance sheet. But they decided to keep quiet about that un=
til after the deal closed.=E2=80=9D
I said above that you don=E2=80=99t often see trickiness in M&A in part bec=
ause it is a cooperative endeavor where everyone is trying to work nicely t=
ogether. Here, though Indap quotes another Kingswood employee saying that =
=E2=80=9Cgiven the contentiousness of the negotiations and the transaction =
with the seller, we made a strategic decision to address the SSI debt post =
close=E2=80=9D with the adjustment. If they already don=E2=80=99t like you,=
 and you already don=E2=80=99t like them, you=E2=80=99re not going to go ou=
t of your way to point out mistakes that hurt them.
And I said above that you don=E2=80=99t often see=C2=A0trickiness=C2=A0in p=
art because, at least for private equity buyers, it=E2=80=99s a repeat game=
 in which reputation is valuable.=C2=A0On the other hand, do you know what =
else is valuable? One hundred nine million dollars. If you are about to clo=
se a middle-market=C2=A0M&A deal for $40 million, and you get a mistaken ba=
lance sheet from the seller that will cause you to unfairly underpay by $50=
0,000, you might, in the spirit of cooperation and fair dealing, email them=
 back to say =E2=80=9Chey you missed $500,000 here, let=E2=80=99s fix that.=
=E2=80=9D And they=E2=80=99ll email back and say =E2=80=9Cthanks=E2=80=9D a=
nd keep the $500,000 and think fondly of you.
But if you get a mistaken balance sheet that=C2=A0will create a $109 millio=
n windfall for you, you might decide to keep the money.=C2=A0

