<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Save Mart</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Merger agreements are long and boring and most=
 people don=E2=80=99t read them all the way through. In theory, this might =
make them a good place for tricks. If you are selling your company, maybe y=
ou could try putting on page 47: =E2=80=9CNotwithstanding anything else in =
this agreement,=C2=A0Buyer shall pay Seller an amount in cash equal to the =
product of (1) the Purchase Price and (2) two (2).=E2=80=9D Maybe no one wi=
ll notice, everyone will sign the contract, you=E2=80=99ll get to closing, =
the buyer will hand you a check for the agreed purchase price, and you=E2=
=80=99ll say =E2=80=9Cno actually on page 47 it says you have to give me tw=
ice this amount.=E2=80=9D The buyer will flip to page 47 and say =E2=80=9Ch=
uh I missed that but come on, that was not the deal,=E2=80=9D you will say =
=E2=80=9Cno, it was the deal, it=E2=80=99s right there in the contract,=E2=
=80=9D you=E2=80=99ll go to court, and the judge will say =E2=80=9Cwell thi=
s is mighty weird but a contract is a contract so here=E2=80=99s your money=
.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In practice, you do not hear much about this s=
ort of thing in big mergers and acquisitions, for several reasons:</p>
<ol style=3D"list-style-type: decimal; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;"=
>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Many mergers are fairly collaborative=
, friendly endeavors. The buyer is buying a business that it likes, it is w=
orking with the seller to make sure the business is as good as possible, ev=
eryone is trying to win each other=E2=80=99s trust, and often it is better =
to win points by saying =E2=80=9Chey we noticed that this formula would und=
erpay you, let=E2=80=99s fix it=E2=80=9D than it is to try to sneak a trick=
y formula into the contract.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Parti=
es to merger agreements have=C2=A0<em>huge=C2=A0</em>incentives to catch tr=
icks, and they pay lawyers to read the contracts and look out for tricks.<a=
 class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transpa=
rent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Mergers are often one-shot deals =
for the seller =E2=80=94=C2=A0after the merger, the target company vanishes=
 =E2=80=94=C2=A0but there are a lot of repeat players around. Private equit=
y firms and big companies do a lot of acquisitions, and developing a reputa=
tion for trickiness might make that harder. Their professionals =E2=80=94=
=C2=A0bankers and lawyers =E2=80=94=C2=A0also do lots of deals, for buyers =
and sellers, and also care about their reputation.<a class=3D"footnote-inde=
x" href=3D"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !imp=
ortant; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bott=
om-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !important; displa=
y: inline-block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>
</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">This is not legal advice, but as =
a broad generalization,=C2=A0if there is something in a merger agreement th=
at is=C2=A0<em>manifestly a trick</em>, and you go to court to enforce it, =
there=E2=80=99s a decent chance that a judge will say =E2=80=9Coh come on t=
hat=E2=80=99s a trick, you can=E2=80=99t enforce that,=E2=80=9D and your tr=
ick won=E2=80=99t work. It=E2=80=99s possible that a judge will say =E2=80=
=9Ca contract is a contract and congratulations on your trick,=E2=80=9D but=
 it=E2=80=99s also quite possible that she won=E2=80=99t, and will be annoy=
ed, and you=E2=80=99ll be in a worse place than if you hadn=E2=80=99t done =
the trick at all.</li>
</ol>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I have become a bit of a connoisseur of contra=
ctual trickiness around here, and also in my previous careers.<a class=3D"f=
ootnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoratio=
n: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000;=
 border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !impor=
tant; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0But mostly I am sort of an efficient-markets guy, in many areas o=
f life, and I tend to assume that most big-dollar high-finance contracts pr=
obably say what people expect them to say.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But last week at FT Alphaville, <a href=3D"htt=
ps://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35042113.285343/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cu=
ZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvN2VmMTU1OWEtMGI3Yy00OGNkLTgwZGMtMDg0MDgxYmVhOGFk/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cBdb30e53a" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">Sujeet Indap had a wild story</a> abou=
t Save Mart, a closely held supermarket whose family owners sold it in 2022=
 to Kingswood Capital Management. Kingswood agreed to pay the sellers $245 =
million, net of cash and debt; at closing, the sellers swept about $200 mil=
lion of cash from the company, and Kingswood wrote them a check for about $=
40 million.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" style=3D"color:=
 #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; borde=
r-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-c=
olor: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a> And then a few months later, Kingswood sent the sellers a bill for $87=
 million, effectively asking them to <em>pay Kingswood=C2=A0</em>for taking=
 over the company. =E2=80=9CThe saga is a window into the vagaries of priva=
te-company dealmaking,=E2=80=9D writes Indap,=C2=A0=E2=80=9Cand how esoteri=
c financial accounting can be weaponised by a canny counterparty.=E2=80=9D =
It=E2=80=99s the rare trick M&amp;A!</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is the trick. Save Mart owned a one-third=
 interest in a joint venture called Superstore Industries. It carried this =
interest on its books as an equity investment. Superstore, meanwhile, had $=
109 million of its own debt, which Save Mart apparently guaranteed, but whi=
ch was not reflected on Save Mart=E2=80=99s balance sheet: Save Mart=E2=80=
=99s balance sheet showed only the $22.5 million value of its equity invest=
ment in Superstore (net of that debt and its partners=E2=80=99 equity inter=
ests). And part of what Kingswood was buying from Save Mart was that equity=
 interest.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The way the purchase agreement worked was that=
, after closing, there was a true-up based on the final balance sheet of Sa=
ve Mart at closing. Basically if Save Mart had more debt than expected, the=
 sellers would have to pay Kingswood for the extra debt: You take the compa=
ny=E2=80=99s actual debt at closing, subtract the debt reflected on the pre=
-closing balance sheet, and the sellers pay Kingswood back an adjustment fo=
r any excess. If the sellers went on a borrowing spree just before closing,=
 and then paid the cash out to themselves, they=E2=80=99d have to pay it ba=
ck to Kingswood in the true-up.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But the purchase agreement=E2=80=99s definitio=
n of =E2=80=9CClosing Date Indebtedness=E2=80=9D included Save Mart=E2=80=
=99s own debt and also debt that it guaranteed. This means that:</p>
<ul style=3D"list-style-type: disc; padding-left: 40px; margin: 16px 0;">=
=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">The $109 million Superstore debt count=
s, under the terms of the purchase agreement, as Save Mart=C2=A0debt at clo=
sing.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">It was=C2=A0<em>not=C2=A0</e=
m>reflected on the pre-closing balance sheet, because it is not Save Mart d=
ebt under accounting rules.</li>=09<li style=3D"margin-bottom: 5px;">Theref=
ore, you take the $109 million debt, you subtract the=C2=A0<em>zero=C2=A0</=
em>dollars of that debt reflected on the balance sheet, and that=E2=80=99s =
the true-up that the sellers owe to Kingswood.</li>
</ul>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Kingswood paid the sellers about $40 million f=
or the company at the closing on March 28, 2022. And then in July, it sent =
them a post-closing statement, asking them to=C2=A0<em>pay it back $87 mill=
ion</em>. (The $87 million apparently=C2=A0reflected the $109 million debt,=
 minus other post-closing adjustments in the sellers=E2=80=99 favor.) So th=
e total purchase price of the company would be negative.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The sellers replied to the effect =E2=80=9Cno =
obviously that debt doesn=E2=80=99t count, that=E2=80=99s not the deal, we=
=E2=80=99re not paying.=E2=80=9D Kingswood replied =E2=80=9Cwell the purcha=
se agreement says it counts, so pay up.=E2=80=9D They went to arbitration, =
and the arbitrator =E2=80=94=C2=A0a former Delaware Chancery Court=C2=A0jud=
ge =E2=80=94=C2=A0<a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/=
35042113.285343/aHR0cHM6Ly9hY3JvYmF0LmFkb2JlLmNvbS9saW5rL3Jldmlldz91cmk9dXJ=
uJTNBYWFpZCUzQXNjZHMlM0FVUyUzQWM3NmU5NjM3LTFjN2YtMzgzMi04MjI4LTk2YzEyM2VlMj=
k1Nw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf5eb2410" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D=
"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: non=
e !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; borde=
r-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">ruled in favor of Kingswood=
</a>, finding that=C2=A0obviously they didn=E2=80=99t <em>mean=C2=A0</em>fo=
r the sellers to have to pay for all that debt, but that=E2=80=99s what the=
 contract <em>says</em>, and a contract is a contract:=C2=A0</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The buyer relies heavily on the definitions in=
 the purchase agreement to argue that the parties contemplated potential do=
wnward adjustments to the purchase price to account for debt that resided w=
ithin the target=E2=80=99s subsidiaries.=C2=A0The seller acknowledges the b=
uyer has not misread the applicable definitions, but argues the proper cons=
truction of those definitions must account for other provisions in the cont=
ract that reflect the parties=E2=80=99 intent that the sizable debt at issu=
e would not be counted in the purchase price adjustment. ...</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Extrinsic evidence, says the seller, reveals t=
hat the parties never intended for the debt at issue=C2=A0to be part of the=
 purchase price adjustment. For its part, the buyer struggles to explain mu=
ch of this extrinsic evidence, but maintains the adjustment is entirely con=
sistent with the parties=E2=80=99 overarching understanding that the sale w=
ould be a cash free, debt free transaction. =E2=80=A6</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Delaware law is more contractarian than most, =
and Delaware courts will enforce the letter of the parties=E2=80=99 contrac=
t without regard for whether they have struck a good deal or bad deal.=C2=
=A0</p>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Kingswood and the sellers then went to the act=
ual Delaware Chancery Court, which disagreed with the arbitrator but had to=
 defer to his decision. So Kingswood gets its money. The sellers are appeal=
ing to the Delaware Supreme Court.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">To be fair, this is not exactly a trick in the=
 contract; it=E2=80=99s a trick in the balance sheet, or perhaps a tricky i=
nteraction between the two. Indap <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbus=
iness.com/click/35042113.285343/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuZnQuY29tL2NvbnRlbnQvN2VmMTU=
1OWEtMGI3Yy00OGNkLTgwZGMtMDg0MDgxYmVhOGFk/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cCdb30e53a=
" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D=
"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px=
; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-colo=
r: #ccc;">quotes the Kingswood deal guy</a>:</p>
<blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">We were surprised that the seller didn=E2=80=
=99t put any SSI debt in their definition of indebtedness as of the closing=
, and our view was, if=C2=A0that=E2=80=99s what they believed and we raised=
 it, we thought=C2=A0it would be a contentious topic=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=
=80=89.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Again, we had had a draft purchase agreement f=
rom them dating back to, you know, December that clearly laid out the debt =
of operating=C2=A0subsidiaries, as well as debt guaranteed by Save Mart=C2=
=A0was, in fact, indebtedness for purposes of the transaction. Again, it=E2=
=80=99s a very standard definition.=C2=A0So no, we assumed that they had re=
ad their own document that they drafted=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=89.=E2=80=
=89</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Because our perspective was, per the purchase =
agreement, SSI debt was to be included in indebtedness. For some reason, wh=
ich we don=E2=80=99t know why, that appeared not to be the perspective of t=
he seller at the=C2=A0time that they delivered the preclosing statement.</p=
>
</blockquote>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Indap writes: =E2=80=9CIn other words, Kingswo=
od had believed, all along prior to signing and closing, that the gross SSI=
 debt belonged on Save Mart=E2=80=99s main balance sheet. But they decided =
to keep quiet about that until after the deal closed.=E2=80=9D</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">I said above that you don=E2=80=99t often see =
trickiness in M&amp;A in part because it is a cooperative endeavor where ev=
eryone is trying to work nicely together. Here, though Indap quotes another=
 Kingswood employee saying that =E2=80=9Cgiven the contentiousness of the n=
egotiations and the transaction with the seller, we made a strategic decisi=
on to address the SSI debt post close=E2=80=9D with the adjustment. If they=
 already don=E2=80=99t like you, and you already don=E2=80=99t like them, y=
ou=E2=80=99re not going to go out of your way to point out mistakes that hu=
rt them.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And I said above that you don=E2=80=99t often =
see=C2=A0trickiness=C2=A0in part because, at least for private equity buyer=
s, it=E2=80=99s a repeat game in which reputation is valuable.=C2=A0On the =
other hand, do you know what else is valuable? One hundred nine million dol=
lars. If you are about to close a middle-market=C2=A0M&amp;A deal for $40 m=
illion, and you get a mistaken balance sheet from the seller that will caus=
e you to unfairly underpay by $500,000, you might, in the spirit of coopera=
tion and fair dealing, email them back to say =E2=80=9Chey you missed $500,=
000 here, let=E2=80=99s fix that.=E2=80=9D And they=E2=80=99ll email back a=
nd say =E2=80=9Cthanks=E2=80=9D and keep the $500,000 and think fondly of y=
ou.</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But if you get a mistaken balance sheet that=
=C2=A0will create a $109 million windfall for you, you might decide to keep=
 the money.=C2=A0</p>
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">Adam Neumann</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Adam Neumann founded WeWork Inc., a company bu=
ilt on short-term=C2=A0office rentals,=C2=A0happy hours, cool vibes, amazin=
g tech-visionary patter and a tech valuation. He tried to take it public, f=
ailed, was ousted with a giant payout, and went off to start a new company =
called Flow that is roughly WeWork but apartments. (Apartment rentals, happ=
y hours, vibes, patter, venture capitalist investors.)</p>
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Meanwhile WeWork went bankrupt <a href=3D"http=
s://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35042113.285343/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuY=
mxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMTEtMDkvYWRhbS1uZXVtYW5uLWlz=
